5. What is the function of macrophages?
That’s right! Macrophages are derived from blood monocytes. They are phagocytic and present antigens to lymphocytes.

Macrophages
Macrophages are derived from blood monocytes. They mature in CT spaces, where they can proliferate locally.
Macrophages are avidly phagocytic cells that are known as antigen presenting cells (APCs). They present antigens to the lymphocytes, therefore participate in immune responses.
Macrophages are relatively small and inconspicuous unless they have been active in phagocytosis. Macrophages are named according to the sites that they reside: Kupffer cells of the liver, Microglial cells of the CNS, Langerhans cells of the skin, Osteoclasts of bone tissue.
